Let $A,$ $B,$ $C,$ $D,$ $E,$ and $F$ be the vertices of the regular hexagon; let $O$ be the center i.e. the centre of the circle. Notice the symmetry in this problem; let $I$ be the intersection of line segments $DE$ and $BC$, and notice $\triangle BOI$ is isosceles. In particular, we can see
\begin{align*}
BO = \frac{a\sqrt{3}}{2}\\
CO = R
\end{align*}
where $R$ is the radius and $a$ is the side of the hexagon. Hence we calculate the other two sides;
\begin{align*}
OI &= \frac{R}{2}\\
EI &= \frac{a\sqrt{3}}{2} - R\\
DI &= R - \frac{a\sqrt{3}}{2}\\
CD &= \sqrt{DI^2 + EI^2} = \sqrt{\left(R - \frac{a\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{a\sqrt{3}}{2} - R\right)^2}\\
CD &= a\sqrt{\frac{3}{2} - \sqrt{3}}
\end{align*}
and substituting $a$ appropriately to get this in terms of $a$ and $R$ gives
\begin{align*}
\frac{CD}{BC} &= \frac{3\sqrt{6 - 4\sqrt{3}}}{5 \sqrt{2 - \frac{4}{3}\sqrt{3}}}\\
\frac{CD}{AB} &= \frac{3 \sqrt{2}\sqrt{3 - 2\sqrt{3}}}{5 \sqrt{6 - 4\sqrt{3}}}\end{align*}
Notice that if $CD/AB = 1$, then $ABC$ would be an equilateral triangle, which would imply $BC/AB = 1$, leading to a contradiction. Hence assume $\frac{CD}{AB} \neq 1$. Then we can simplify to
$$\frac{CD}{AB} = \frac{\sqrt{2}\sqrt{3 - 2\sqrt{3}}}{5 \sqrt{6 - 4\sqrt{3}}}$$
Hence we have 
$$\frac{3 \sqrt{2}\sqrt{3 - 2\sqrt{3}}}{5 \sqrt{6 - 4\sqrt{3}}} = \frac{m}{n} \iff \frac{\sqrt{2}\sqrt{3 - 2\sqrt{3}}}{5 \sqrt{3 - 2\sqrt{3}}} = \frac{m}{n}$$
Hence we simplify and get
$$\frac{1}{5} = \frac{m}{n} \implies m = 1, n = 5 \implies m + n = \boxed{6}.$$
</think> <answer $\boxed{6}$ </answer>

